SIMPLE: wayment
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wayment
<hw>Way"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Waymented</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Waymenting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>waymenten</ets>, OF.
<ets>waimenter</ets>, <ets>gaimenter</ets>, <ets>guaimenter</ets>, from
<ets>wai</ets>, <ets>guai</ets>, woe! (of Teutonic origin; see
<er>Woe</er>) and L. <ets>lamentari</ets> to lament. See
<er>Lament</er>.]</ety> <def>To lament; to grieve; to wail.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>waiment</asp>.]</altsp>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thilke science . . . maketh a man to <qex>waymenten</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For what boots it to weep and <qex>wayment</qex>,⟦br⟧
When ill is chanced?</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wayment</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wayment
<hw>Way"ment</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Grief; lamentation;
mourning.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>waiment</asp>.]</altsp>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

